{
  "answer": "One such moment occurs at the poem's conclusion, in the speech of the \"wise in spirit\" (*snottor on mode*), where human grief over earthly mutability resolves into Christian consolation.[^1] The original text reads:\n\n> Wel biþ þam þe him are seceð,  \n> frofre **to fæder on heofonum**, **þær us eal seo fæstnung stondeð.**\n\nThe caesura (half-line break) after *heofonum* creates a dramatic pause at the height of supplication: the first half-line voices the wanderer's (or humanity's) yearning turn toward God amid sorrow (\"comfort to Father in the heavens\"). The second half-line then delivers the transcendent resolution from a divine vantage—the eternal, unchanging stability (*fæstnung*) awaiting in heaven. This structural pause enacts the theological pivot, interrupting mortal lament to affirm heavenly permanence.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, [The Wanderer](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-5bdc65).\n\n[^2]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, [The Wanderer](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/original/). The half-lines follow standard Old English alliterative verse conventions, as preserved in the *original* variant.",
